# Visualizing the value distributions of each variable
categorical_columns = [col for col in data_set.columns if data_set[col].dtype == 'object']
numerical_columns = [col for col in data_set.columns if data_set[col].dtype != 'object']
num_categorical_columns = len(categorical_columns)
num_numerical_columns = len(numerical_columns)
num_rows = (num_categorical_columns + num_numerical_columns) // 3 + (1 if (num_categorical_columns + num_numerical_columns) % 3 != 0 else 0)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, 3, figsize=(15, 5*num_rows))
axes = axes.flatten()

# Categorical column plots
for i, col in enumerate(categorical_columns):
    sns.countplot(x=col, data=data_set, ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f'{col} Frequency')
    axes[i].set_xlabel(col)
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Count')
        # Add counts above each bar
    for p in axes[i].patches:
        axes[i].annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.0f'), 
                         (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), 
                         ha = 'center', va = 'center', 
                         xytext = (0, 5), 
                         textcoords = 'offset points')

# Numerical column plots
for j, col in enumerate(numerical_columns):
    sns.kdeplot(data=data_set[col], ax=axes[i + j + 1], fill=True)
    axes[i + j + 1].set_title(f'{col} Distribution')
    axes[i + j + 1].set_xlabel(col)
    axes[i + j + 1].set_ylabel('Density')

for k in range(i + j + 2, len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[k])

plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.3)

# Checking for outliers in the train dataset using quantiles
numeric_columns = data_set.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns

Q1 = data_set[numeric_columns].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = data_set[numeric_columns].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

outliers = ((data_set[numeric_columns] < lower_bound) | (data_set[numeric_columns] > upper_bound))
outliers_count = outliers.sum()

print(f'Number of outliers for each numerical variable:\n{outliers_count}')


plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))

for i, column in enumerate(numeric_columns, 1):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i)
    plt.boxplot(data_set[column].dropna())
    plt.title(f'Outliers - Box plot of {column}')
    plt.ylabel(column)

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# We have 614 rows in our dataset, which is actually somewhat low for credit modeling.
# The number of outliers are reasonable since we don't expect all values to be in this range.
# We will remove some of the max and min values of incomes and loan amount term for better model accuracy.
# The multiple applications with a 480 month request are relevant data points for us, they will not be removed.

# We will make a copy of the dataset to use from this point
# Since both the incomes of applicant and co-applicant are equally responsible, we can make a new column named Total_Income and use this for modeling.
# We can drop the prior income columns since we no longer need them, their data is represented in Total_Income.
# We can also set the Loan_ID column as index, since its not really relevant as a variable.
data_set_copy = data_set.copy()

data_set_copy.set_index('Loan_ID', inplace=True)

# Create 'Total_Income' and drop the other income columns
data_set_copy['Total_Income'] = data_set_copy['ApplicantIncome'] + data_set_copy['CoapplicantIncome']

data_set_copy.drop(['ApplicantIncome', 'CoapplicantIncome'], axis=1, inplace=True)

In[13]:
# Perform chi-square test for each categorical variable
chi2_results = {}
for col in categorical_columns2:
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(data_set_copy[col], data_set_copy['Loan_Status'])
    chi2, p_value, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
    chi2_results[col] = {'chi2': chi2, 'p_value': p_value}

# Print chi-square test results
for col, results in chi2_results.items():
    print(f"Test results for '{col}':")
    print(f"  Chi-square value: {results['chi2']}")
    print(f"  p-value: {results['p_value']}")
    if results['p_value'] < 0.05:
        print(f"{col} is likely relevant to loan approval.")
    else:
        print(f"{col} is likely irrelevant to loan approval.")
    print()

# Logistic Regression Model
numerical_features = ['Total_Income','LoanAmount','Loan_Amount_Term']
categorical_features = ['Education', 'Credit_History', 'Property_Area','Married']
target = 'Loan_Status'

class_mapping = {'Y': 1, 'N': 0}
y_encoded = data_set_copy[target].map(class_mapping)

# Put more weight on loan rejections since its more important for us to estimate the bad credit
weights = {False: 1.4, True: 1}

# Encode categorical variables
X_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data_set_copy[numerical_features + categorical_features], columns=categorical_features)
y_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data_set_copy[target])

# Train-test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_encoded, y_encoded, test_size=0.3, random_state=43)

y_train_labels = y_train.iloc[:, 1]  
y_test_labels = y_test.iloc[:, 1] 

# Train the  model
model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=4000, class_weight= weights)
model.fit(X_train, y_train_labels)

y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate model performance
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_labels, y_pred)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")

print(classification_report(y_test_labels, y_pred))

# Loan Rejection:
# Precision: 76% of loans predicted to be rejected are actually rejected.
# Recall: Only 52% of truly rejected loans are correctly identified.

# Loan Approval:
# Precision: 79% of loans predicted to be approved are actually approved.
# Recall: 92% of truly approved loans are correctly identified.

# Overall, the model performs well in identifying approved loans. 
# It struggles more with correctly identifying risky loans for rejection, potentially increasing financial risk.

# Gradient Boosting Classifier
numerical_features = ['Total_Income', 'LoanAmount','Loan_Amount_Term']
categorical_features = ['Education', 'Property_Area', 'Credit_History','Married']
target = 'Loan_Status'

# Encoding categorical variables
X_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data_set_copy[numerical_features + categorical_features], columns=categorical_features)
y_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data_set_copy[target])

# Split the dataset into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_encoded, y_encoded, test_size=0.3, random_state=43)

y_train_labels = y_train.iloc[:, 1]  
y_test_labels = y_test.iloc[:, 1] 

# Initialize and training the model
gradient_boosting = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=100, learning_rate=0.1, random_state=43, max_depth=3)
gradient_boosting.fit(X_train, y_train_labels)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred = gradient_boosting.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate model performance
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_labels, y_pred)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")

print(classification_report(y_test_labels, y_pred))

# GBM has also given us quite similar results to logistic regression
